                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12515417" author="bayard" created="Wed, 25 Jul 2007 20:55:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Digging around, it looks like 2.0 does support the feature - &apos;consume remaining&apos;. It defaults to &apos;--&apos; and you can set what the flag is.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So this falls into the big question of &apos;what next?&apos;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12515523" author="russel" created="Thu, 26 Jul 2007 06:44:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think there needs to be a decision as to whether 2.x is a live line of activity.  If it is then there needs to be a release so that people can switch to it.  If there is no enthusiasm for a 2.x release and switching to it as the supported line, then features like this need to be retrofitted to the 1.x line and perhaps a 1.2 issued with all the new stuff.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12515524" author="brianegge" created="Thu, 26 Jul 2007 06:48:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Many Unix programs have the &amp;#8211; option, such as Ruby &amp;amp; Perl.  I think it&apos;s a good to have, but I have to disagree that&apos;s it&apos;s a bug.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You could &apos;preprocess&apos; the args and use CLI 1.1, or you could look at using the 2.0 branch.  It would be good to get some development on the 2.0 branch.  There are a number of things the 1.x branch doesn&apos;t do, but would be really useful to have.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For example, I usually have a help &amp;amp; version option.  If either of these options are present, then nothing else should be, and &apos;required&apos; arguments become &apos;not required&apos;.  2.0 has build in handling for this situation.  What I do now though, is process the arguments twice.  Once for help/version, and if neither are present, then I do the regular parse.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12519678" author="bayard" created="Tue, 14 Aug 2007 14:03:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think there&apos;s enough interest in 2.0 for us to start pushing in that direction.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are a bunch of issues closed already with &quot;2.0 does this&quot;, so this issue is going to go the same way. Marking as WONTFIX.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12519696" author="russel" created="Tue, 14 Aug 2007 14:45:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;OK, this works for me but... 2.0 is not in the Maven repository.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I will raise an issue.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
